\title{Polynomials form a real vector space}
\author{alex-nelson}
\import{notation}
\date{2025-12-08}
\taxon{example}
\import{ela}

\p{Let us write down the set of all polynomials in one unknown #{x} with real coefficients as #{\RR[x]}. When equipped with polynomial addition as vector addition, and scalar multiplication just multiplies each coefficient "in the obvious way", then this forms a real vector space.}
